./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:16:- **Critical changes**: full system health scan (all imports, gates, services, logs)
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:20:This pattern applies at every level: conversation agents, sdp-cli pipeline agents, the daemon, and this Introspector service. The Introspector is the autonomous embodiment of this loop — running 24/7 without human intervention.
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:46:1. **All 8 data sources** — daemon log, pipeline log, I/O guard log, event stream, watchdog log, Observatory DB, health check output, systemd journal
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:47:2. **Full autonomy with verification** — auto-fix anything, but every fix must pass generate/verify/fix with a cross-provider agent before applying. Only ask permission for destructive actions (delete data, restart daemon, modify production config).
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:48:3. **Separate systemd service** — independent from the daemon. Can diagnose daemon issues, restart independently, run at its own pace.
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:73:| DS-1 | Daemon log | `tools/cypherclaw_daemon.log` | 2 min | Exceptions, tracebacks, repeated errors |
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:79:| DS-7 | Health check | Telegram health check messages | 5 min | Stale data, tracebacks in health output |
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:90:| IN-005 | Create `introspector/fixer.py` — given a diagnosis, generate a fix using one agent, then verify with a DIFFERENT provider agent. Fix types: code_patch (modify a .py file), config_change (modify .json/.toml), process_restart (systemctl restart), cache_clear (delete stale files), db_repair (sqlite3 recover). Only apply fix if verification passes. Destructive actions (restart daemon, delete data, modify promptclaw.json) require Telegram approval from Anthony. | T2 |
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:92:| IN-007 | Create systemd service file `introspector.service`. Runs as user service, auto-restart on failure, depends on redis and cypherclaw-daemon. Wrap in I/O protection (ionice -c3 nice -n19). Start after daemon. | T1 |
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:94:| IN-009 | Implement Observatory integration. Record all findings and fixes as Observatory events. Track: errors_detected_per_hour, fixes_applied_per_day, mean_time_to_detect, mean_time_to_fix, fix_success_rate. Feed into the daemon's health check display. | T2 |
./my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:97:| IN-012 | Seed known_patterns with common errors observed so far: dev_task empty description, SQLite WAL corruption, stale sdp-cli status cache, pipeline lock file stale, Redis connection refused after reboot, missing tmpfs venv, health check traceback from corrupt DB. Each pattern includes regex, severity, and resolution template. | T1 |
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:17:1. **Unhealthy Ollama excluded from candidate list** — `QuotaMonitor._runtime_unavailable_agents()` calls `_refresh_local_provider_status()` on every `get_available_agents()` invocation. When `ollama_health.check_health()` returns `False` for all configured ports, the local provider is blocked and all agents mapped to it are added to the `blocked` set. These are excluded before both the healthy/warn filter and the fallback max-headroom selection.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:21:3. **Recovery when Ollama returns healthy** — Health is checked live (not cached between calls) in `_refresh_local_provider_status`. When any configured port returns healthy, `ollama` re-enters `fallback_candidates` and the standard selection path on the next call. No restart or manual intervention required.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:29:- All cloud providers also quota-paused AND Ollama unhealthy: `get_available_agents` returns `[]`, `_eligible_agents` returns `[]`, `select` raises `ValueError("no agents available for selection")` — correct escalation behavior.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:30:- Partial port recovery: any healthy port re-admits Ollama (documented tradeoff, see Consistency).
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:34:**Test coverage**: Two new targeted tests cover exclusion, fallback, and recovery paths at both the `QuotaMonitor` and `AgentSelector` levels. The `autouse` `_healthy_ollama` fixture correctly protects pre-existing tests from the new live health check.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:39:- Alert message updated to use runtime-specific language (`"runtime health recovers"` vs `"headroom recovers"`) for local providers — consistent with how quota vs runtime degradation is differentiated elsewhere.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:40:- The multi-port `any()` semantics (healthy if any port is up) is a deliberate design decision noted in ESCALATIONS.md: a single-socket outage does not block Ollama if another socket is healthy. This is consistent with the "best-effort local routing" philosophy and correctly documented.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:44:No security concerns. The `importlib.import_module("agent_selector")` call inside `_local_provider_ports` reuses an already-imported module from the same path — no new import-path attack surface beyond what existed before. No secrets, credentials, or user-controlled input flows into health check calls. `ollama_health.check_health(port)` takes an integer port, not a URL derived from external input.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:51:- The renamed test (`test_ollama_never_excluded_from_selection` → `test_ollama_excluded_from_selection_when_unhealthy_and_recovers`) accurately describes the new behavior.
./sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:65:2. The multi-port `any()` granularity tradeoff is correctly escalated. If the team later decides per-route exclusion is needed (e.g., route Ollama category A to port 11434, B to 11435, and fail independently), that would be a separate task.
